Intro:

Our group found that the priority ranking was a vague indicator of the differences among the impaired water bodies. The majority of the impaired water bodies on the 303d list were ranked as a 3, which We looked for relationships between priority ranking and basin, cause, and use. We further investigate the causes of water body impairment in the 2018 data to disseminate trends.

Priority ranks

The priority ranks are defined as:

1 = Current Priorities are those site/pollutant combinations being addressed by TMDL or alternative restoration plans being developed during the 2016-2018 time-frame.

2 = Near Term Priorities are those site/pollutant combinations being addressed by TMDL or alternative restoration plans being developed during the 2019-2022 time-frame.

3 = Long Term Priorities are those site/pollutant combinations being addressed by TMDL or alternative restoration plans being developed after 2022.

Priority rank and use

Uses of all sites assessed for 2018 303d list. The basin regions are outlined in dark grey.

Uses are as follows:

  • AL = Aquatic Life
  • FISH = Fish consumption
  • REC = Recreation
  • SHELLFISH = Shellfish Harvesting

Count of uses and priority.

Aquatic life contains the only impairment listed as a priority ranking of 1, meaning the only impaired water body being actively addressed is classified as AL. Fish is the only use that does not contain a priority ranking other than 3. Recreational and shellfish include 2 and 3 rankings. A priority rank of 3 being the majority of rankings across all uses.

Although aquatic life is the majority use (n=590), we were surprised to find that it is the only use that had was being addressed or had a developing plan for addressing pollutants because we assumed water bodies being used for shellfish, fish, and recreation pose a larger threat to human health.
